======================================================================
PART 3: TRIBONACCI IN THE EISENSTEIN LATTICE
======================================================================

  Tribonacci sequence: [0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 4, 7, 13, 24, 44, 81, 149, 274, 504, 927]

  Tribonacci Eisenstein norms N(T_n, T_{n+1}):
    n= 0: N(    0,     0) =        0
    n= 1: N(    0,     1) =        1
    n= 2: N(    1,     1) =        1
    n= 3: N(    1,     2) =        3
    n= 4: N(    2,     4) =       12
    n= 5: N(    4,     7) =       37
    n= 6: N(    7,    13) =      127
    n= 7: N(   13,    24) =      433
    n= 8: N(   24,    44) =     1456
    n= 9: N(   44,    81) =     4933
    n=10: N(   81,   149) =    16693
    n=11: N(  149,   274) =    56451

  Tribonacci constant tau = 1.8392867552
  tau^2 - tau + 1 = 2.5436890127
  This is N(1, tau) in the continuous sense.
  N(1, tau) = 1 - tau + tau^2 = 2.5436890127
  tau^3 = 6.2222625231
  tau^2 + tau + 1 = 6.2222625231 (= tau^3)
  So tau satisfies Phi_3(tau) = tau^3 - 1/(tau-1)... no.
  tau^3 - tau^2 - tau - 1 = 0
  (tau-1)(tau^2) = tau + 1? No: tau^3 = tau^2 + tau + 1
  So tau^2 + tau + 1 = tau^3 = Phi_3(tau)... wait:
  Phi_3(x) = x^2 + x + 1. Phi_3(tau) = tau^2 + tau + 1 = tau^3!
  So Phi_3(tau) = tau^3. The tribonacci constant is a FIXED POINT
  of x |-> Phi_3(x)^(1/3) in some sense.

  KEY INSIGHT: Phi_3(tau) = tau^3
  Phi_3(2)   = 7   (forbidden)
  Phi_3(4)   = 21  (forbidden)
  Phi_3(tau) = tau^3 = 6.222... (irrational!)
  The tribonacci constant is where Phi_3(x) = x^3,
  i.e., the INTERSECTION of the cyclotomic polynomial
  and the cube function.

